We were also curious about the fitting passages in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But how you get used to it at NFS is much different in the final effect than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is shrunk at by some superfluous errors that are present in this series for more or less years.
So it's actually no more mistakes, but rather signs of an incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you sit down on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first one in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race takes place on a different route and that the stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't have the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still very nice to see, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So there's nothing world moving.
But the journey through the desert, through autumn landscape or high above through deep snowy landscape works visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, untypical elements bring a little variety into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which greatly limits the view.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be very careful not to be thrown by an avalanche.
On the other hand, the individual races are built in quite well in a row.
It's just a few, but they're rich.
For a while one tries to overwhelm the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then one has time to pick up (classical race against the stopwatch), then another personal duel awaits with a single opponent.
And for that, too, the police are mingling in, trying to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It's more about some interactive animations in which Jack is fleeing from anyone and where the player has to help by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that in the game there are much less passages than one would expect (mostly only three).
Finally, this is more of a benefit, because this element has at least no chance of becoming boring - it belongs in the context of the above-mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model runs into the footsteps of the previous parts.
In other words, seeing from today's point of view, it doesn't rip trees, on the other hand, it could not be said that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look around elsewhere.
But a action-packed race will continue to be quite fair to this model, even though one could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems appear only after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
From a game of this kind it is hardly expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no impact on any object of how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: In some places, when you overwhelm or pass by on the opposite cars, you just "stiff" the other car easily, in other, almost identical situations, you get to shake and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the car's going to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, this doesn't matter, from annoyance it's all the time.
The restarts are so solved: if you have total damage or land far off the route, then throw the game back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
If you've exhausted them, everything's going off the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart doesn't even help, as nothing helps to learn the critical section from the head.
