If one wanted to look for a suitable word that characterized IBM's strategy most precisely, then this would probably be the word "long-live".
For the general public, IBM is the synonym for technological revolution, and it is known as a modern company, although since its inception, it has been extended for a century.
The basis for this longevity already laid its first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Even he represented the slogan that countless global problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" thus became a trademark for the life of the future giant (and, at the same time, the title of the company's internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of the company culture prepared by Watsen.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a sustainable movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was also successful for a whole century because it remained faithful to its principles and did not hold back from changing everything else around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society over the course of our first century.
We hope we will be able to do more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, today's director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Appreciative system
Watson operated social care for his employees in the 1930s - in the same way as the businessman Baňa in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid a holiday as one of the first American employees, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a thoughtful reward system for best newcomers and dealers.
