IBM History: From cheese tailor to world-wide flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took it only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone to the later company IBM set the fusion of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They owned technologies such as the famous Stechcard Watches for registering the start-up and end-of-work.
As the architect of this new company, Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who appointed the head of the competition firm Thomas J. Watson to help him with the management of the company.
This leader even put IBM's founders in the shadow - Watson's ideas are based on the company's invincible culture and identity to this day.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as already the name reveals, began to manufacture and sell all kinds of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese tailors to checkouts.
During the first four decades of Watson's leadership, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped the NASA lead flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully getting into the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off over the last three years is the concept of "smarter planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a smart way in areas not even planned so far, e.g. in order to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the trade sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform to help dealers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-level top research team that deals with the technology of voting recognition.
