Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the ČSSR: Čedok, sportsurist, CKM, Recrea and autoturist.
At the time, travel agencies mainly sold travels to the socialist East Block countries, and in the West only were allowed to choose at the time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a provincial course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of these socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovakian) to travel freely within the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travels would not be possible.
Even back then, travel agencies also offered travels to the West, but then one had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for leaving the West - was only given "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most Czechs therefore spent their holidays domestically, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 total revolution followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While by 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, one of which is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic by 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation was abolished in the neighbouring western European countries, which created a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time the Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their journeys to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
This was how Czech holidaymakers slept on trips to Paris in the tent in the park, because who already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at the time.
A typical feature when traveling abroad from the Czech Republic was a trunk filled with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely interchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus also the average salaries rose, which resulted in a further important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips after 1997 through charter flights, making flight travels incredibly reduced thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already had no exchange of payments with all the advanced countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-smart" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in distant sunny countries every year; this year twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 csd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the epoch, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely included our country among the advanced countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 Tsd. CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the costs at the resort.
