The decline in economic activity by November has continued to increase unemployment in the Mexican state. Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March 55,053 inhabitants had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, unemployment has risen to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6,19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa this year dates back to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the policies of the public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are watching at present is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, there are market liquidity losses due to the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are forbidden to accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, which is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there. These people stay here and are looking for work here, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black-worked
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when taking into account the high proportion of unskilled work, which, according to INEGI, covers 60.38 percent of the workers employed in the country without paying into social security funds.
