Asphalt's tough behaviour means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very tenacious and almost solid at 50°C, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes on one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The research of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible street floor, composed of six layers of materials, the last of which contained the three asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this layer of wear has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move forward and the forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of forces in the road floor.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"On the wear layer," he said, "is designed a last layer, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
The majority of the forces received and distributed by this road covering also requires an adequate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further important factors to be considered, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates into the layer and is only difficult to get out of it. This causes a evaporation of all layers of the road floor and, as a result, the occurrence of knockholes.
When a punch is created," he said, "the cover layer will first be removed, while the wear layer will not be affected until after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained by adequate maintenance programs during the first signs."
The member of the Sisthema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of road covering must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent shock holes.
