Entry of a "Golden household rule" into the Constitution
The government of the largest Social-Democrat/Christian-Democrat coalition in Austria decided on Tuesday to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid any possible degradation from rating agencies in the top-bonity of Austria (AAA).
It was the S & D Chancellor Werner Faymann very personally who announced this decision of the Council of Ministers, although the public Austrian government debt is 74.6%, that is far above the 60 % criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but significantly below the debt level of the countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay did not fall on a stroke from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an additional three billion euros each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Minister of Foreign Affairs.
Austria is also calling for the Brussels Summit of Eurozone Member States to be held on 26 October: Heads of State or Government would then have called for the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 as well as a return to the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or by the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian Government is similar to the "German model" because Germany was the first European country to have incorporated such a "rule" into the constitution.
By 2017, the structural deficit should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, while the government's structural deficit should not exceed the 0.35% of GDP from 2017 onwards, whereas regional states and municipalities should also have balanced households.
In the 2020/21 horizon, the objective is to eliminate budget debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement.
