All of this explains the wide smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin in terms of gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an excellent technology.
The underwater line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at about 200 m deep.
During its construction, mine fields dating from World War II had to be diverted.
"Some hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed cautiously," said Jens Müller, spokesperson of the Nord Stream company.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long loop of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which has been interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers did not, since the Sweden did not want to see a Russian state-owned society settled in a permanent manner at the level of its coasts.
"In the case of a havary, we close the gas transmission in less than a minute," explained Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered to be little probable by the constructors, as the silences were estimated to be a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The state control of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel and a device circulated inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measuring a meter in diameter, is introduced into the inner pipe and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of the forwarding by the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformations of the metal upon its arrival.
The gas pipeline has been designed to work for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF (15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gas Union and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then rented the entire capacity of its gas transport, on renewable twenty-years contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transporter gas volume falls," explained Jens Müller.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% of shareholders as well as 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For example, for GDF Suez, the total investment amounted to 240 million.
The minority shareholders, however, are prepared to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline occurs on a sandy, forested coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre high valves form the gas outlets.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other metrics of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
